I am working on a patch to consume MCTP UUID's. This is needed to handle cases where multiple endpoint ID's are implemented by the FD and UUID is the mechanism to distinguish.

using MctpInfo = std::pair<EID, UUID>;
using MctpInfos = std::vector<MctpInfo>;

virtual void handleMCTPEndpoints(const MctpInfos& mctpInfos) = 0;

This patch set is for MctpDiscovery to support multiple managers and then MctpDiscovery has a unified interface to execute different manager's callback function. So, the code changes I am going to submit can do the thing like below.

std::unique_ptr<platform_mc::Manager> platformManager =
    std::make_unique<platform_mc::Manager>(event, reqHandler, dbusImplReq);
std::unique_ptr<MctpDiscovery> mctpDiscoveryHandler =
    std::make_unique<MctpDiscovery>(
        bus, std::initializer_list<pldm::IMctpDiscoveryHandler*>{
                 fwManager.get(), platformManager.get()});

The purpose of loading static EID table is for the MCTP layer which does not implement /xyz/penbmc_procject/mctp D-Bus interface(e.g. mctp-demux)

By the way, this patch set is part of the implementation of this design proposal(https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/docs/+/47252).The whole code changes can be found in this abandoned patch set(
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/pldm/+/51115). I split it into multiple small patch sets for easy review.

I've already tried this, but everything is still the same (I'm talking about line 77 of the 'mctp_endpoint_discovery.cpp' file, for example, or line 130 in the same file).

I've written a simple example demonstrating this:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <variant>
#include <cinttypes>
#include <vector>

using NetworkId = uint32_t;

using Value =
    std::variant<bool, uint8_t, int16_t, uint16_t, int32_t, uint32_t, int64_t,
                 uint64_t, double, std::string, std::vector<uint8_t>>;

int main()
{
    Value val(123u);
    std::cout << std::get<NetworkId>(val) << std::endl;
}
```

If we add '123u', it works. But if we write just '123', it fails.

In my case, it looks like this:
```
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::bad_variant_access'
  what():  std::get: wrong index for variant
[1]    72286 IOT instruction (core dumped)  ./a.out
```

It seems to me that the "under the hood" value is set to "int", so it fails.

Do I understand correctly that in your case nothing breaks at this stage?
